## gRPC API

Install the locked Buf toolchain once per development environment. New RPC responses already contain required non-optional `code` and `msg` fields; add business fields from field number 3:

```bash
jgo tools install
jgo rpc pbapi add RPCName --service {{.ServiceName}}
# Edit request fields and add response business fields from number 3 in
# api/proto/{{.PackageName}}/v1/service.proto.
jgo rpc generate
jgo list
```

`jgo doctor` and generation fail if any local or imported RPC response is missing the standard `code/msg` fields.

`jgo rpc generate` overwrites generated protobuf and transport files, but never overwrites an existing business service method.
Generated business methods use `<Service><RPC>` names, so mixed projects can safely use the same operation name over HTTP and gRPC. `jgo call grpc` displays zero values for non-optional fields; unset `optional` fields remain omitted.
An explicit `jgo/errors.Error` returned by a business method becomes an `OK` gRPC Response with its `code/msg`. Unknown errors, panics, cancellation, and timeouts use non-`OK` gRPC status codes.

Named outbound gRPC dependencies are configured under `rpc_client` in `configs/local.yaml` and managed with `github.com/eyesofblue/jgo/client/grpcx`. Connections are lazy, the default unary timeout is 3 seconds, the earlier of the client timeout and caller context deadline wins, and unavailable dependencies do not block startup or affect `/healthz`.

Use `jgo rpc server add <Service> --module <module>@<version>` to implement a Service from a shared proto module. Use `jgo rpc client add <Service> --module <module>@<version> --name <name>` to inject its typed client as `Service.RPC.<Name>`. JGO discovers a unique generated package automatically; use `--package` when the same Service exists in multiple protobuf API versions.

The client name is a stable config/code identifier and cannot be renamed. Change address, timeout, and TLS values directly under `rpc_client.<name>` in YAML.
